26
00:01:04.780 --> 00:01:08.080
So first of all, thanks for taking time to consider the bill, and the object, as

27
00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:11.640
you no doubt know, is to modernize the military justice system by making it simpler

28
00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:15.010
and easier to navigate. In doing so, it'll help the New Zealand Defense Force,

29
00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:18.830
which I'll henceforth refer to as NZDF, to better direct its time and

30
00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:22.240
resources to delivering core operational outputs while maintaining an effective,

31
00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:25.100
portable, and expeditious system of discipline.

32
00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:29.560
In 2019, several external reviews examined aspects of the military justice system,

33
00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:31.180
including the summary trial process.

34
00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:35.160
These reviews identified that parts of the system were inefficient, overly

35
00:01:35.220 --> 00:01:37.880
complicated, and time-consuming, particularly for low-level

36
00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:42.280
disciplinary offenses. In addition, investigatory powers were

37
00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:46.780
seen to be outdated and have not kept pace with developments in technology.

38
00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:49.800
Mr. Chair, I don't know if other members of the committee

39
00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:53.750
have spent time on the Justice Committee such that they'd be very familiar with

40
00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:57.610
these themes in the civil justice system as a whole, but I know that there

41
00:01:57.640 --> 00:02:01.580
is good faith commitment across the House of Parliament to examine

42
00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:03.080
those in that separate realm as well.

43
00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:06.940
But I just make the obvious point that while part of the thrust of this bill is to

44
00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:11.000
align, to a large extent, civil and military systems of justice,

45
00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:14.860
there's also sort of a parallel work stream in which

46
00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:18.200
both are seeking to become more efficient in some of the ways that I will shortly

47
00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:18.720
describe.

48
00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:23.640
An example of the more close alignment is that the bail

49
00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:27.380
provisions will be amended to align with the Bail

50
00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:30.780
Act. The use of national security information in court proceedings will apply the

51
00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:34.090
framework used by civilian courts under the Security Information and Proceedings

52
00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:38.200
Act, and provisions to address disruptive behavior and contempt of court are, of

53
00:02:38.260 --> 00:02:40.660
course, aligned with the Contempt of Court Act.

54
00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:44.220
A new search warrant framework will require judicial oversight of searches

55
00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:48.420
of electronic devices and searches by NZDF

56
00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:51.420
military police of areas outside a defense area.

57
00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:55.120
These search powers have been designed to be consistent with the New Zealand Bill

58
00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:58.400
of Rights Act 1990 and the Search and Surveillance Act.

59
00:02:58.540 --> 00:03:01.500
The bill also aims to improve other aspects of the military justice system by

60
00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:05.080
introducing a new minor disciplinary sanction system that offers an

61
00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:08.760
alternative pathway to address low-level offending, creating additional safeguards

62
00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:12.230
on the use of detention as a punishment at summary trial, transferring

63
00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:16.080
responsibility for serious, complex, or sensitive offending out of the chain of

64
00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:17.590
command, the military chain of command,

65
00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:22.340
to the Director of Military Prosecutions, introducing new provisions to

66
00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:25.769
conduct drug and alcohol testing for disciplinary purposes, and extending the right

67
00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:29.740
to elect trial by court martial in all cases other than minor

68
00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:30.900
disciplinary offenses.

69
00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:36.200
Mr. Chair, I flag now that the remarks I'm about to make

70
00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:40.360
relate to a new proposal in terms of the government's decision-making,

71
00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:44.420
and I do understand that you've had the benefit of a briefing previously from Naval

72
